comment:
* Class representing the target user of a policy set by an admin
 * (set from {@link DevicePolicyManager}), this is passed in to
 * {@link PolicyUpdateReceiver#onPolicySetResult} and
 * {@link PolicyUpdateReceiver#onPolicyChanged}.

variables.name: LOCAL_USER_ID
variables.comment:
* Indicates that the policy relates to the user the admin is installed on.
     *
     * @hide

variables.name: PARENT_USER_ID
variables.comment:
* For admins of profiles, this indicates that the policy relates to the parent profile.
     *
     * @hide

variables.name: GLOBAL_USER_ID
variables.comment:
* This indicates the policy is a global policy.
     *
     * @hide

variables.name: UNKNOWN_USER_ID
variables.comment:
* Indicates that the policy relates to some unknown user on the device.
     *
     * @hide

variables.name: LOCAL_USER
variables.comment: * Indicates that the policy relates to the user the admin is installed on.

variables.name: PARENT_USER
variables.comment: * For admins of profiles, this indicates that the policy relates to the parent profile.

variables.name: GLOBAL
variables.comment: * This indicates the policy is a global policy.

variables.name: UNKNOWN_USER
variables.comment:
* Indicates that the policy relates to some unknown user on the device. For example, if Admin1
     * has set a global policy on a device and Admin2 has set a conflicting local
     * policy on some other secondary user, Admin1 will get a policy update callback with
     * {@code UNKNOWN_USER} as the target user.
